## 🌐 HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)

- Protocol used for communication between browser and web server
- Used to load websites (HTML, images, videos)

### How it works:
- Browser sends **HTTP Request**
- Server sends **HTTP Response**

---

## 🔒 HTTPS
- Secure version of HTTP
- Encrypts communication between browser and server

---

## 🔗 URL (Uniform Resource Locator)

A URL tells the browser where and how to access a resource.

### Parts of a URL:

- **Scheme** → HTTP / HTTPS  
- **User (optional)** → username:password  
- **Host** → domain name (e.g., tryhackme.com)  
- **Port** → 80 (HTTP), 443 (HTTPS)  
- **Path** → location on server (`/blog`)  
- **Query String** → extra data (`?id=1`)  
- **Fragment** → section of page (`#section`)  

---

## 📤 HTTP Requests

Example request:

GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: tryhackme.com
User-Agent: Firefox
Referer: https://tryhackme.com/


### Important parts:
- **Method** → GET, POST, PUT, DELETE  
- **Host** → target website  
- **User-Agent** → browser info  
- **Referer** → where request came from  

---

## 📥 HTTP Responses

Example:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Content-Type: text/html
Content-Length: 98

<html>...</html> ```
Includes:
Status code
Content type
Content length
Response body (actual data)
🔧 HTTP Methods
GET → Retrieve data
POST → Submit data (create)
PUT → Update data
DELETE → Remove data
📊 HTTP Status Codes

Server responses that indicate what happened.

Categories:
🔹 1xx – Informational
Request received, continue
🔹 2xx – Success
200 OK → Request successful
201 Created → Resource created
🔹 3xx – Redirection
301 → Moved permanently
302 → Temporary redirect
🔹 4xx – Client Errors
400 → Bad request
401 → Unauthorized
403 → Forbidden
404 → Not found
🔹 5xx – Server Errors
500 → Internal error
503 → Service unavailable
💡 Why status codes matter:
Finding vulnerabilities
Discovering hidden pages (403)
Debugging server issues
Useful in SOC analysis and penetration testing
📑 HTTP Headers
Request Headers (Browser → Server)
Host → target website
User-Agent → browser info
Content-Length → size of data
Accept-Encoding → compression support
Cookie → stored session data
Response Headers (Server → Browser)
Set-Cookie → stores session data
Cache-Control → how long to store data
Content-Type → type of content
Content-Encoding → compression type
🍪 Cookies
Small pieces of data stored in browser
How they work:
Server sends cookie (Set-Cookie)
Browser stores it
Browser sends it back with future requests

Used for:

Login sessions
User tracking
🧱 How Websites Work
Basic Flow:
Browser sends request
Server responds (HTML, CSS, JS)
Browser renders the page
🔹 Front-End (Client Side)
HTML → structure
CSS → design
JavaScript → behavior
🔹 Back-End (Server Side)
Server logic (Python, PHP, Node.js)
Database (user data, passwords)
Authentication systems
⚠️ Sensitive Data Exposure

Occurs when websites accidentally expose important data.

Causes:
Leaving test data
Comments in source code
Exposing secrets in frontend
Usage:
Helpful in penetration testing
Viewing page source can reveal hidden data
💉 HTML Injection

Occurs when user input is not filtered.

Example:
User inputs: <h1>Hacked</h1>
Website displays it as actual HTML
Risks:
Fake login forms (phishing)
Misleading messages
Data manipulation
🔄 Putting It All Together
User requests a website
DNS resolves IP
Browser sends HTTP request
Server responds with data
Browser renders website
⚡ Load Balancing
Uses multiple servers instead of one
Distributes traffic efficiently
Sends requests to available/fastest server
🌍 CDN (Content Delivery Network)
Stores content in multiple locations worldwide
Sends data from nearest server
Improves speed and performance
🛡️ WAF (Web Application Firewall)
Protects web applications
What it checks:
URL
Input fields
Headers
Payloads
Blocks:
SQL Injection
HTML Injection
Bots
DDoS attacks
Difference:
Firewall → protects network
WAF → protects web applications
🖥️ Web Servers
Software that delivers website content
Stores website files
Virtual Hosting
One server can host multiple websites
🔚 Full Web Flow

User → Browser → Web Server → Backend → Database → Server Response → Browser Display
